title: Please read and be informed!
description:
When you undermine my instructions, you're undermining the farmer.  I get my instructions from them. 

Leviticus 19:9-10 "When you reap the harvest of your land, do not reap to the very edges of your field or gather the gleanings of your harvest. 10. Do not go over your vineyard a second time or pick up the grapes that have fallen. Leave them for the poor and the foreigner. I am the Lord your God."

The produce we glean is for our neighbors in need. We don't pay for it and we ask that no one sells it.  Some farms have produce stands and if you can afford it, support our farmers by buying at their stand. (I normally include info on email.)

SoSA relies on the farmer to call me, I don't call them.  They plan, but it doesn't mean it will be ready. Hint: weather and many other reasons.

We get a short notice, 3-4 days and sometimes 1 day. An e-mail goes out immediately, or as soon as I can. I may also call depending on number of people needed.

Please DON'T show up to a farm unannounced and definitely don't wander around the farm.  It is rude and disrespectful to the farmers.  

Spots are limited and they're first come first serve basis.  PLEASE NOT NOT ask me to add you automatically, if I do it for one, I'd have to do it for everyone. If the event is at capacity, let me know you wish to be put on a waiting list, if someone cancels I will contact you.

ONE EMAIL per person.  Please don't sign up two people using the same email address. Remember, spots are limited and when unregistered volunteers show up, it causes delays and may cause problems with the farm.  I rely on the farm to tell me how many spots to open. 

We accept volunteers of all ages, children under 16 must be with an adult and no need to sign them up online.  Let me know ahead of time and I will have a paper waiver to fill out.  This will allow an adult to have that spot. If your teen needs volunteer hours, I will sign them.  If they drive themselves, their driving time is included. 

We glean for 2 hours only and that includes leaving for the field, so I ask that you arrive at least 15 minutes early. IF you are late, you will be left behind.  This is to respect the farmers and everyone else who showed up on time.

Gleanings are from 8-10am, with the exception of a farm in Concord. We glean from 7:30-9:30.

Sometimes we may have the chance to return to the field as second time, however most of the time the farm is waiting for us to finish so they bushhog the field and get it ready for the next crop. See picture!

Most of our farms do not have a bathroom for us to use and the woods do not count as one.  Please plan accordingly!

A handwashing station is provided, (soap/water) you are welcome to bring your own clean gloves.  If using gloves, we ask that you keep up with them so we don't litter the field.  It can get stuck in farm machinery and cause expensive damage.

If you are taking produce back to an agency, information must be provided prior to gleaning, (address, EIN, contact info, etc.)  Also, anyone delivering produce must bring their own boxes to transport the gleanings.

If you have a clean bucket, please bring it, they are easier to carry in a field than boxes.

It gets HOT in the field, if you need a break take it.  Wear a hat and bring plenty of water to drink.

No pets are allowed and service dogs are left to the farmer's discretion,  it must be cleared prior to the date of gleaning.      

Dress for the occasion.  Closed toe shoes required! Fields can be muddy and tennis shoes are not practical. 

Sometimes we may all drive our vehicles to the field, sometimes just trucks and other times no vehicles are allowed and we will all ride on a wagon, oh... and sometimes we walk. Please follow instructions and if you have questions, ask.  Don’t assume that you can drive your vehicle just because “there is space”.

We glean when the agencies are open, Monday-Friday. 

If you have a large group call me about spaces.  If we schedule months in advance, the chances of something coming up are slim to none.  Again, we work work with the farmer, not the other way around. 

If you read all this.... THANK YOU and give yourself a high five. :)

title: Urge Your TX Rep to Protect Voting Rights: VOTE NO on HB 5337/SB 16
description:
The Texas Legislature needs to hear from you! Contact your Texas House Representative urging them to VOTE NO! 

HB 5337/SB 16 would create unnecessary barriers for Texans trying to register to vote by requiring proof of citizenship, such as a passport or birth certificate. This bill adds extra hurdles to an already burdensome process, even though the state would still be responsible for verifying citizenship through its own systems. In the end, it makes voter registration harder without solving any real problems.

HB 5337/SB 16 will do more harm than good, disproportionately impacting eligible voters, especially young people, seniors, and naturalized citizens, who might not have these documents readily available and whose status is likely more difficult to verify. 

The bottom line is that our elections are already secure, but what they aren’t is fully accessible. We should be working to build a democracy where every voice is heard, not one where more are shut out.

title: East Kentucky Community Remembrance Project Service Day 2025
description:
On Saturday, May 24th, the East Kentucky Community Remembrance Project and the Big Sandy Chapter of Kentuckians For The Commonwealth are organizing a free community lunch and service project in Wayland, Kentucky.

We will gather at 9:30am in Wayland to get organized for the morning service project clearing brush from a nearby cemetery where many Black residents, including some who were enslaved people, are buried. We'll leave most cars at the Wayland Community Center and shuttle in a few vehicles to the nearby cemetery.

There will be a rideshare and caravan departing Prestonsburg at 8:30am from the parking lot behind the Town Center shops at 152 N Lake Dr, Prestonsburg, KY 41653. If anyone would like a ride, or to follow a driver who knows their way to Wayland, please reach out to Eric Fields at eric@kftc.org.

We hope this service project is a step on a path towards racial understanding, healing, justice, and transformation. Because of previous service projects, we expect to mostly be clearing weeds and very young trees and brush.

We need volunteers, but we also recognize that clearing trees and brush isn't a good fit for all folks. All are welcome to enjoy lunch and fellowship from 12:30pm - 3:00pm at Wayland Community Center, whether or not you also sign up for the morning work crew. There will be a donation jar to help cover the costs of lunch, but lunch is free and everyone is welcome.

We'll use this time to learn and reflect on the history of the local community, including the heritage of many local Black families, some of whom remain and many who have moved away from the area. We will discuss a specific incident of racial violence, the lynching of a Black man named Fred Shannon, that took place at the Wayland jail in October of 1924. We will also hold a ceremony in which we place a historical marker at the old Wayland jail, the site of Shannon's killing. The historical marker has been provided to the EKY Community Remembrance Project by the Equal Justice Initiative. You can learn more about the work they do [HERE](https://eji.org/).

Please RSVP if you plan to join us on May 24th and let us know what parts of the day you will attend.

If more than one member of your household plans to attend, please register each person separately to help us estimate how much food to prepare. Thank you.

People of all ages are welcome for lunch. Working volunteers must be 16 years or older.

It is important to protect everyone's health and safety during this event. We will provide sun screen, water, and a first aid kit. We ask everyone to bring their own water bottle, work gloves, and sturdy shoes. If you do not have the necessary safety items, let us know and we'll follow up with you to make a plan.

The Wayland Community Center is located at 2662 King Kelly Coleman Hwy, Wayland, KY 41666. It will be on the right on Rte. 7, 3.9 miles after turning off of Rte. 80
